---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'why-indonesia', text: 'Why Retirees Choose Indonesia', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-options', text: 'Visa Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-access', text: 'Healthcare Access', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Cost Planning', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Indonesia Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/indonesia/insurance' },
  { title: 'Thailand for Retirees', href: '/insurance-for/retirees/in/thailand' },
  { title: 'Senior Insurance', href: '/best/senior-insurance' },
  { title: 'Budget Expat Insurance', href: '/best/budget-expat-insurance' },
  { title: 'Malaysia for Retirees', href: '/insurance-for/retirees/in/malaysia' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'ageLimit', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'preExisting', header: 'Pre-Existing' },
  { key: 'indonesiaNetwork', header: 'Indonesia Network' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly (Age 60)' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', ageLimit: '74', preExisting: 'Covered (24mo wait)', indonesiaNetwork: 'Good (Bali, Jakarta)', monthly: '$300-450' },
  { provider: 'Pacific Cross', ageLimit: '70', preExisting: 'Case-by-case', indonesiaNetwork: 'Excellent', monthly: '$220-360' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', ageLimit: '74', preExisting: 'Moratorium option', indonesiaNetwork: 'Good', monthly: '$280-420' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', ageLimit: '74', preExisting: 'Case-by-case', indonesiaNetwork: 'Adequate', monthly: '$240-380' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'item', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'notes', header: 'Notes' },
];

const costRows = [
  { item: 'International Insurance (55-59)', monthly: '$220-340', notes: 'Comprehensive coverage' },
  { item: 'International Insurance (60-64)', monthly: '$300-450', notes: 'Comprehensive coverage' },
  { item: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: '$400-580', notes: 'Comprehensive coverage' },
  { item: 'Local Indonesian Insurance', monthly: '$40-80', notes: 'Limited coverage' },
  { item: 'Direct medical costs (Bali)', monthly: '$50-100', notes: 'Out-of-pocket routine care' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Retirees in Indonesia | Bali Retirement Guide 2026"
  description="Complete guide to health insurance for retirees in Indonesia and Bali. Second Home Visa, Retirement KITAS, healthcare options, and costs for Western retirees."
  headline="Health Insurance for Retirees in Indonesia"
  subheadline="Bali has become synonymous with affordable tropical retirement. But Indonesia's healthcare has limitations, and medical evacuation matters. Here's the practical guide for retirees."
  heroImage="/images/countries/indonesia-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Retiree Quotes"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mb-4">
    <strong>Affiliate disclosure:</strong> We may earn a commission when you click our links and purchase insurance. This doesn't affect our recommendations or the price you pay.
  </p>

  <h2 id="overview" class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Overview</h2>

  <p class="mb-4">
    Indonesia—particularly Bali—has attracted retirees for decades with its affordable living, spiritual culture, and natural beauty. The Second Home Visa (2022) finally created a legitimate long-term residency option for wealthy retirees, while the Retirement KITAS remains available for those over 55.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-4">
    The challenge: Indonesia's healthcare outside Jakarta is limited. Bali has improved but still lacks facilities for serious conditions. Medical evacuation to Singapore is standard protocol for anything complex. International insurance isn't optional—it's essential.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-8">
    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-3">Key Facts for Retirees</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Visa:</strong> Second Home Visa (5-10 years) or Retirement KITAS (55+)</li>
      <li><strong>Insurance required:</strong> Yes, for both visa types</li>
      <li><strong>Public healthcare:</strong> Not accessible to foreign retirees</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of living:</strong> 60-70% lower than US/UK (Bali slightly higher)</li>
      <li><strong>Medical evacuation:</strong> Singapore (2.5 hours) for serious conditions</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="why-indonesia" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Why Retirees Choose Indonesia</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Bali's Unique Appeal</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Bali offers something no other retirement destination matches: spiritual culture, stunning nature, established expat community, and tropical climate—all at affordable prices. Ubud provides artistic, wellness-focused retirement. Seminyak and Canggu offer beach lifestyle. Sanur suits those wanting quieter, more traditional Bali.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Exceptional Affordability</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    A comfortable retirement in Bali costs $1,500-2,500/month including villa rental, food, entertainment, and healthcare. That's 60-70% less than comparable Western lifestyles. Domestic help, massages, and dining out are remarkably cheap. Outside Bali (Lombok, Java), costs drop further.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Established Expat Infrastructure</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Decades of Western visitors have created robust expat infrastructure. English is widely spoken in tourist areas. International restaurants, yoga studios, coworking spaces, and expat groups abound. Finding community is easy. Finding Western products and services is straightforward.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Climate Considerations</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Tropical climate means heat and humidity year-round (27-33°C). Dry season (April-October) is ideal; wet season brings daily rain. Bali's elevation varies—Ubud is cooler than coastal areas. Air conditioning is essential. Not suitable for those who struggle with heat.
  </p>

  <h2 id="visa-options" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Visa Options</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Second Home Visa (2022)</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Indonesia's newest long-stay option grants 5-10 year residence. Requirements: proof of $130,000+ in liquid assets (bank statements), health insurance, and clean criminal record. No age requirement. Ideal for wealthy retirees wanting long-term security. Can be extended without leaving.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Retirement KITAS (55+)</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    The traditional retirement visa for those 55 and older. Requirements: $1,500/month pension or proof of funds, health insurance, Indonesian sponsor (usually arranged by visa agent), and commitment not to work. Valid 1 year, renewable annually. More affordable than Second Home Visa but requires yearly renewal.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Insurance Requirement</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Both visas require proof of health insurance valid in Indonesia. Coverage must include emergency medical treatment. International health insurance from recognized providers qualifies. Local Indonesian insurance may be accepted but international coverage is strongly recommended.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Practical Reality</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Most retirees use visa agents to handle the bureaucracy—costs $500-1,500 for the service. The process involves paperwork, waiting, and visits to immigration. Plan 2-3 months from application to visa in hand. Renewals are simpler than initial applications.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Need Visa Insurance for Indonesia?"
    description="Get coverage that meets Indonesian visa requirements and includes evacuation."
    buttonText="Get Indonesia Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Insurance Requirements</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Visa Compliance</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Indonesian visa applications require health insurance documentation. The policy must cover Indonesia and include emergency treatment. International health insurance from major providers meets requirements. Present your policy certificate with your visa application.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Medical Evacuation Is Essential</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    This is non-negotiable in Indonesia. Bali's hospitals handle routine care adequately but lack facilities for serious conditions—cardiac surgery, cancer treatment, complex trauma. Standard protocol is evacuation to Singapore (2.5 hour flight). Ensure your policy covers $100,000+ in evacuation benefits without restrictive definitions.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">What to Look For</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Prioritize: medical evacuation (critical), inpatient coverage, direct billing with Bali international hospitals (BIMC, Siloam), outpatient coverage, and pre-existing conditions if applicable. Repatriation coverage matters if you want the option of returning home for treatment.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Pre-Existing Conditions</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    If you have existing health conditions, comprehensive coverage is especially important in Indonesia—you can't rely on local healthcare for complex management. Cigna's guaranteed acceptance covers pre-existing after 24 months. Pacific Cross reviews case-by-case. Get covered before conditions progress.
  </p>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Recommended Providers</h2>

  <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Pacific Cross — Best for Indonesia</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Regional specialist headquartered in Bangkok. Excellent network across Southeast Asia including Indonesia. Direct billing at BIMC Bali, Siloam hospitals, and Jakarta facilities. Understands regional healthcare realities. Lower premiums than global insurers. Strong choice for retirees staying in Southeast Asia.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Cigna Global — Best Evacuation Coverage</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Global network with robust evacuation services. Coordinates medical transport to Singapore or home country smoothly. Guaranteed acceptance option for pre-existing conditions. Higher premiums but comprehensive peace of mind. Good for retirees wanting maximum security.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Allianz Care — European Option</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    German-headquartered with good Asian networks. Moratorium underwriting option for pre-existing conditions. Competitive pricing. Strong choice for European retirees who may return to Europe for care.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Local Indonesian Insurance</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Local insurers (AXA Indonesia, Prudential Indonesia) offer cheap coverage but limited scope and claims processes can be challenging. May satisfy visa requirements but insufficient for serious medical needs. Best viewed as supplement, not primary coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Indonesia Insurance Options"
    description="See actual costs for your age and situation. No obligation quotes."
    buttonText="Get Personalized Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="healthcare-access" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Healthcare Access in Indonesia</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Bali Healthcare</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    BIMC Hospital (Kuta and Nusa Dua) provides international-standard emergency and routine care with English-speaking staff. Siloam Hospital offers broader services. Kasih Ibu Hospital handles general care. For anything complex—cardiology, oncology, neurosurgery—evacuation to Singapore is standard.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Jakarta Healthcare</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Jakarta has Indonesia's best hospitals: Pondok Indah, Siloam Semanggi, RS Premier Bintaro. Quality approaches Singapore for many conditions. If you retire near Jakarta, healthcare options are significantly better than Bali. But most retirees choose Bali for lifestyle reasons.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Singapore Evacuation</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    For serious conditions, Singapore is the evacuation destination. Mount Elizabeth, Gleneagles, and Singapore General Hospital handle complex cases. Flight time is 2.5 hours from Bali. Medical evacuation services coordinate air ambulance or commercial flight with medical escort. This is why evacuation coverage matters.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Pharmacies and Medications</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Pharmacies in Bali stock common medications, often without prescriptions required. Prices are low. For specialized medications, availability varies—bring supplies from home or order from Singapore. Counterfeit medications exist; use reputable pharmacies attached to hospitals.
  </p>

  <h2 id="costs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Cost Planning</h2>

  <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Total Healthcare Budget</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    For a 60-year-old retiree in Bali: international insurance with evacuation ($300-450/month) plus out-of-pocket routine care ($50-100/month) totals roughly $350-550/month. This provides comprehensive coverage including Singapore evacuation if needed.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>High deductible:</strong> A $2,500-5,000 deductible reduces premiums 25-35%. Routine care in Bali is cheap enough to self-fund. <strong>Asia-only coverage:</strong> Excluding Americas significantly reduces costs. <strong>Inpatient-only:</strong> Cover hospitalizations and evacuation; pay cash for outpatient.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Don't Cut Evacuation</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Whatever else you economize on, maintain robust evacuation coverage. A medical flight to Singapore costs $15,000-30,000 out of pocket. Complex treatment in Singapore can run $50,000-200,000+. This is not the place to save money.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 mb-8">
    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Is Bali safe for retirees?</h3>
      <p>Bali is generally very safe. Violent crime against foreigners is rare. Petty theft exists but is manageable with normal precautions. Traffic is the main danger—motorbike culture requires caution. Most retirees feel safer than in major Western cities. Natural disasters (earthquakes, volcanic activity) are periodic risks.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Do I need to speak Indonesian?</h3>
      <p>In Bali's expat areas (Ubud, Seminyak, Canggu, Sanur), English works well. Outside these areas and in healthcare settings, Indonesian helps. Basic Indonesian is easy to learn and appreciated. For serious medical situations, international hospitals have English-speaking staff.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">What happens in a medical emergency?</h3>
      <p>Call your insurance's emergency line immediately. For true emergencies, go to BIMC Hospital. Your insurance coordinates stabilization, then evacuation to Singapore if needed. Having your insurance card and emergency contact readily accessible is important. Consider a medical ID bracelet.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Can I get insurance with pre-existing conditions?</h3>
      <p>Yes, but it matters more in Indonesia because local healthcare can't manage complex conditions. Cigna offers guaranteed acceptance with 24-month waiting period. Pacific Cross and others review case-by-case. Get comprehensive coverage—you can't rely on Indonesian healthcare as a backup.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Which area of Bali is best for retirees?</h3>
      <p>Sanur is quietest—established, calm, good for older retirees. Ubud offers culture, yoga, cooler temperatures. Seminyak/Canggu are livelier, younger, more developed. Amed and north Bali are remote but peaceful. Most retirees start in Sanur or Ubud, then explore.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">What about healthcare for chronic conditions?</h3>
      <p>Routine management of diabetes, hypertension, etc. is possible in Bali. BIMC can handle monitoring and medications. For complex management or complications, Singapore is the option. If you have serious chronic conditions, consider whether Indonesia's healthcare limitations are acceptable.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Retire in Indonesia?"
    description="Get insurance sorted before your move. Evacuation coverage is essential."
    buttonText="Get Your Indonesia Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mt-12">
    This information is for educational purposes. Visa regulations, insurance options, and healthcare quality change. Verify current visa requirements with Indonesian embassies. Consider consulting with Indonesia-based expat advisors for your specific situation. Last updated: May 2026.
  </p>
</PageShell>
